The HD 33564 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 33564 is a star with 1.25 times the mass of the Sun, and NaN times its radius. It is located 68.34 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 3 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 33564 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 33564 system


HD 33564 b

HD 33564 b was discovered by the Haute-Provence Observatory observatory, in 2005-12, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 1.10 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 33564 b is 2893.800 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 33564 b is 12.500 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 33564 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
